Brazilian Stock Movers: Amil, BR Malls, JBS, MMX Mineracao, PDG

-- B y   N e y   H a y a s h i
-- 
2011-05-11T13:57:18Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-11/brazilian-stock-movers-amil-br-malls-jbs-mmx-mineracao-pdg.html
The following companies are having
unusual price changes in  Sao Paulo  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 9:26 a.m. New York time.
Preferred shares are usually the most-traded class of stock.  The Bovespa Index fell 1 percent to 64,273.35.  Amil Participacoes SA (AMIL3)  (AMIL3 BS) jumped 4.5 percent to
19.38 reais. The Brazilian health insurer reported first-quarter
adjusted net income of 89 million reais ($55 million), a 10
percent increase from a year earlier.  BR Malls Participacoes SA (BRML3)  (BRML3 BS) advanced 3.4 percent
to 17.79 reais.  Brazil ’s biggest owner of shopping malls
yesterday sold 37.4 million shares at 17.20 reais each to raise
643.3 million reais, according to a regulatory filing. An
additional 5.1 million shares may be sold in the next month to
meet excess demand, the filing said.  JBS SA (JBSS3)  (JBSS3 BS) rose 4.1 percent to 5.85 reais. The
world’s biggest beef producer posted first-quarter net income of
147 million reais, or 6 centavos a share, a 48 percent increase
from a year earlier, according to a regulatory filing. The
company was expected to post a profit of 2 centavos a share,
excluding some items, according to the average of four analysts
in a Bloomberg survey.  MMX Mineracao & Metalicos SA (MMXM3 BS) climbed 1.5 percent
to 9.24 reais. The iron-ore producer controlled by Brazilian
billionaire  Eike Batista  said in a filing first-quarter net
income was 63.8 million reais ($39.8 million), which compares
with a loss of 76.1 million reais a year earlier. The company
was expected to post a profit of 55.4 million reais on an
adjusted basis, the median of three estimates on a Bloomberg
survey.  PDG Realty SA Empreendimentos & Participacoes (PDGR3 BS)
slid 2.3 percent to 8.97 reais. The homebuilder led declines by
companies that depend on credit growth as traders raised bets
for higher borrowing costs after data showed inflation quickened
more than expected in Brazil. The first preview of the IGP-M
inflation report from the Getulio Vargas Foundation in  Rio de
Janeiro  rose 0.7 percent, exceeding the median forecast for a
0.39 percent increase in a Bloomberg survey of 15 economists.  To contact the reporter on this story:
